04624nam a22007335i 9781442682580DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162006onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013939186  a97814426825807 a10.3138/97814426825802doi  a(DE-B1597)465051  a(OCoLC)944177326  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPN2654b.J47 2006 7aPER0110002bisacsh04a792.02/22221 aJestrovic, Silvija, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTheatre of Estrangement :bTheory, Practice, Ideology /cSilvija Jestrovic. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGerman and European Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Knight’s Move: From Theory to Theatre -- t2. Some Old Photos: Russian Formalism in Russian Avant-garde Theatre -- t3. Epic Theatre in the Age of Mechanical Reproduction -- t4. In the Hands of Angelus Novus: Form and Ideology -- tAfterword: Retro Estrangement -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a world flooded with information, images, and sounds ? where the distinction between real and simulated becomes increasingly blurred ? one of the most pressing concerns of the theatre is how to subvert the stock responses of an audience and make the well-known fresh and meaningful again. Situating the practice of theatrical estrangement firmly in its social and political contexts, Theatre of Estrangement looks at how this concern has manifested itself in Russian and German avant-garde theatre.Silvija Jestrovic traces the concept of estrangement from its early formulation in the Russian Formalist School of Literary Criticism embodied in the experiments of the Russian avant-garde, to its so-called apotheosis in the theory and practice of Bertolt Brecht. Drawing from a variety of sources ? theatrical performances, dramatic works, visual art, film, political events, biographical data ? she demonstrates that theatrical estrangement is not only an abstract theoretical postulate, but also a practical artistic strategy shaped by the cultural and historical climate. In the historical avant-garde, Jestrovic argues, estrangement became a way of thinking, a means of comprehending the world, and even a lifestyle. Yet, devices of making the familiar strange are destined to erode in one historical and cultural context and become rediscovered in another to rejuvenate stale art forms and open the door to a fresh and more critical perception of reality. Theatre of Estrangement attempts to make that rediscovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExperimental drama, Germany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental drama, Russiany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aExperimental theaterzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aExperimental theaterzSoviet UnionxHistory. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268258040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682580423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682580.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK